[normal] were referred to interchangeably
[normal]. This 
[normal]weaken
[normal]s
[normal] support for U
[normal]C and
[normal] cause
[normal]s
[normal] unnecessary concern.
[normal] The UC roll-out must seek to avoid replicating these communication errors. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.7
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Recommendations:[bold]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The [bold]DWP [bold]should [bold]commit to a full [bold]review of affordability in the [bold]housing benefit[bold] sub-market[bold] and [bold]to [bold]up-rate LHA rates if necessary[bold] to ensure [bold]that [bold]low income households can access accommodation[bold]&#xa0;[bold]3[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Social Secto[bold]r [bold]Size C[bold]riteria[bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]With the 
[normal]introduction
[normal] of the 
[normal]social 
[normal]sector size
[normal] 
[normal]criteria
[normal] (the so called ‘bedroom tax’)
[normal] 
[normal]in April 2013, 
[normal]660,000 people living in council or housing association homes had their [bold]housing benefit[bold] reduced as they had one or more rooms[bold] judged to be “spare bedrooms”[bold]. Hard-pressed fami
[normal]lies on the lowe
[normal]st incomes
[normal] now 
[normal]need to find an average of £14 per week out of already stretched b
[normal]udgets to cover the shortfall. 
[normal]Some will be unable to pay this shortfall and will 
[normal]cut back
[normal] on essential spending on food and 
[normal]household bills
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]O
[normal]thers may
[normal] 
[normal]tak
[normal]e
[normal] out debt, joining the one million households who used a pay day loan to cove
[normal]r their housing costs last year, while 
[normal]many
[normal] may risk arrears, eviction and homelessness. This increases
[normal] costs for local authorities and undermines social housing as the last truly
[normal] affordable housing option for families on low incomes. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]I[bold]f[bold] [bold]households cannot[bold] cover the difference there is not necessarily anywhere for [bold]them[bold] to move[bold] to, meaning they will be unable to escape the penalty[bold]. Because social landlords have tended to build homes to last families for many years, there is a lack of smaller one and two bed flats for households to downsize into. This is true nationally but 
[normal]is
[normal] 
[normal]a particular problem in certain areas.
[normal] 
[normal]For example, i
[normal]n S
[normal]cotland we know
[normal] that
[normal] of the 82,500 households affected by the social sector size criteria, 60,000 need to move to a 1 bedroom p
[normal]roperty to avoid the pe
[normal]nalty.
[normal] 
[normal]C
[normal]urrently around 20,000 
[normal]one
[normal] bedroom properties are let annual
[normal]ly
[normal] across the whole of Scotland in 
[normal]the
[normal] social sector
[normal]. 
[normal]Downsizing could[bold] actually[bold] increase the [bold]housing benefit[bold] bill, for example if affected households move into [bold]more expensive alternatives such as [bold]the private rented sector, a [bold]higher cost[bold] social rent property (likely if transferring to newer acc[bold]ommodation or from council to housing association[bold] accommodation) or into an A[bold]ffordable [bold]R[bold]ent [bold](up to 80% market rent) [bold]property. [bold]&#xa0;[bold]3.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Homeless households should not be penalised by the social sector size criteria.  [bold]H
[normal]omeless households living in local authority owned temporary accommodation (TA) 
[normal]should be 
[normal]exempt fro
[normal]m the 
[normal]under occupation
[normal] penalty. 
[normal]This is particularl
[normal]y a problem in Scotland where 56
[normal]% of 
[normal]TA
[normal] is local authority owned rather than leased or 
[normal]licensed
[normal] from a
[normal] 
[normal]social or private landlord
[normal] where different subsidy rules apply. By definition, househ
[normal]olds who are forced to stay in TA
[normal] unt
[normal]il a settled home is available 
[normal]are vulnerable and in stressful situation
[normal]s
[normal] and in particular need of a stable home to get back on their
[normal] feet.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The calculation of how many bedrooms a household needs is a crude assessment which takes little account of the legitimate needs of disabled people [bold]and others [bold]for additional space[bold]. Shelter has been approached by families who have good reasons for their ‘spare’ bedrooms, 
[normal]for example where
[normal] they need space to store essential medical equipment. Only very limited exemptions have been granted for disabled 
[normal]children
[normal] and
[normal] 
[normal]the DWP continues t
[normal]o maintain that the over-stretched 
[normal]DHP
[normal] fund is the best way to support disabled households.
[normal] However,
[normal] there is no guarantee that this will happen, and families have no right to appeal if DHP is not granted.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]I
[normal]n 
[normal]the case of 
[normal]Burnip, Gorry and Trengrove
[normal] the Court of Appeal ruled that 
[normal]housing benefit
[normal] regulations and not DHPs
[normal] should cater for disabled children who cannot share a bedroom due to different caring needs. 
[normal]Where 
[normal]the 
[normal]DWP wish to support hard cases it would be more appropriate to do so via statuto
[normal]ry regulations, which provide guaranteed protection, rather than unpredictable DHPs. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Even if DHPs were an appropriate tool to protect hard cases, the additional money that has been made available is unlikely to be sufficient. For example there is no guar
[normal]antee that the
[normal] 
[normal]additional £25 million in 
[normal]intended to support disabled people living in homes with expensive adaptations
[normal] will be sufficient, and it is certain that many other disabled people will not be awarded a DHP
[normal]. 
[normal]In England it has been calculated that the DHP budget [bold]can [bold]only[bold] help one[bold] in every 15 of [bold]all[bold] households affected[bold] by the bedroom tax[bold] and in Scotland it is [bold]1 in 17 (6 per cent[bold]), which means that a significant number of vulnerable people will not have access to[bold] a much-needed DHP payment.[bold]  
