[normal]Recommendations:[bold]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]All claimants should be assessed for financial capability[bold] at the start of their claim, and APAs [bold]put in place for those who are not ready for Standard Payments [bold]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]C[bold]laimants who need APAs upfront [bold]must be a priority;  Local Delivery Partnerships could lead on this [bold]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Households should have the option to self-refer [bold]for an assessment for A[bold]P[bold]As [bold]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]H[bold]ouseholds in TA [bold]should [bold]automatically receive APAs[bold].[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]5[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Universal Credit - 13 W[bold]eek [bold]P[bold]rotection[bold]&#xa0;[bold]5.1[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In a little discussed move, short-term protection against rent arrears for people who have recently lost their job will be abolished under [bold]UC[bold]. Currently if someone 
[normal]has not claimed 
[normal]housing benefit
[normal] in the previous 52 weeks and could afford their rent when they signed up to a tenancy, 
[normal]they can claim 
[normal]housing benefit
[normal] for their full rent for 13 weeks. Under the 
[normal]UC
[normal] this will be removed. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Housing benefit is subject to a num
[normal]ber of regulations that limit the amount that can be paid out. This frequently means that people eligible for 
[normal]housing benefit
[normal] are not able to claim sufficient support to cover their actual rent.
[normal] This is especially likely to affect private tenants as LHA ra
[normal]tes are purposely set below “average” rents. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.3[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A comparison of median rents across Broad Rental Market Areas and LHA rates shows that a family renting a typical three bedroom home would have to make up more than £100 a month in over a quarter (27%) of loca
[normal]l authority areas in England if the 13 week protection rule is abolished. In more than two in five (43%) of local authorities families will have a shortfall of more than £75 a month.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.4[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]he 13 week protection rule
[normal] is intended to give people sufficient time t
[normal]o find work and resume paying their rent independently or, if their circumstances are unlikely to improve, make a planned move into cheaper accommodation. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.5[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The majority of people 
[normal]who lose their job 
[normal]will only experience a short-term spell of unemployment. 
[normal]Of the 325,000 unemployment claims that came to an end in June 2013, 53% of claimants were in receipt of JSA for 13 weeks or less
[normal]. Shelter’s concern is that without an adequate safety net, people will be unable to bounce back and will be anxious about how
[normal] they will pay their housing costs at a time when they should be focused on getting bac
[normal]k into work. For some, 
[normal]inadequate support will tip them into arrears, eviction and homelessness. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]5.6[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Recommendations:[bold]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 13 week protection rule must be replicated under [bold]UC[bold], in a way that is compatible[bold] with a unified benefit system[bold]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The DWP [bold]should [bold]publish an impact assessment of the loss of the 13 week protection rule. [bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]6[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Discretionary Housing Payments[bold]&#xa0;[bold]6.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Shelter is extremely concerned that Discretionary Housing Payments 
[normal](DHPs) are being called upon inappropriately to support people with a predictable and clearly defined additional need, when statutory regulations would be better placed to avoid unintended consequences.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Concerns with DHPs:[bold]They are discretionary[bold] - People cannot guarantee they will receive support, even if their circumstances are those that Ministers had in mind when releasing additional funding.  
[normal]They are short-term[bold] –
[normal] 
[normal]Although guidance does state that indefinite awards can be made if a claimant’
[normal]s circumstances are unlikely to change
[normal],
[normal] local authorities are wary of doing this as it makes it harder to budget. Where a shortfall is ongoing and predictable people shouldn’t have to go through repeated applications.
[normal]They are cash-limited[bold] – The allocation
[normal] of DHP given to local councils is cash limited and insufficient to respond to everyone with a shortfall. The need to make the budget last throughout the year can also encourage local authorities not to publicise DHPs or to reject applications earlier in t
[normal]he year in case of a surge in demand later. Local authorities can top-up the DWP allocation by 1.5 times but are legally prohibited from spending anything beyond this. Moreover, many are unable to do so because of pressures on their budgets.  
